entry.title: Ensure allocations go through ParitionAlloc by not calling back to Rust
entry.content:
The allocation hooks were calling back to the Rust global allocator

but on Windows, the Rust stdlib implements its own allocator on top

of the process heap which can't be intercepted by PartitionAlloc.



So, instead, go through the system allocation methods like malloc()

and friends, mimicing the behaviour of the Rust global allocator on

unix to handle large alignments.



On Windows, we use `_aligned_malloc()` and `free()` together which is

incorrect with the Win32 system libs, but is okay with PartitionAlloc

(and is also what is done in base::AlignedMemory).



Also fix the signature of __rust_dealloc: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/master/library/alloc/src/alloc.rs#L33

entry.title: Mac: explicitly mark browser windows as primary for Stage Manager
entry.content:
It looks like there's some window collection behavior back compat

around Stage Manager that looks at full screen but it's not perfect.

Specifically, when we strip NSWindowCollectionBehaviorFullScreenPrimary

on starting a drag, this leaves the window unable to claim its own

Stage Manager group. Restoring full screen primary behavior (which

we weren't doing before but I am adding in this change as a freebie)

is *not* sufficient to mark the window as a Stage Manager primary.



This change explicitly marks browser windows with

NSWindowCollectionBehaviorPrimary where available, and strips and

restores it in the same place where we strip and restore

NSWindowCollectionBehaviorFullScreenPrimary to prevent newly

dragged windows from immediately banishing their source window.

entry.title: [rust] Enable more libc cfg options.
entry.content:
Rust's libc is built as part of the Rust standard library. In our

standard library builds, we are unable to run build.rs scripts to

determine the appropriate configuration options. This CL more accurately

update the config option list to those which would be created by

build.rs against a modern Rust compiler.



In particular, this adds libc_union, which is necessary for Android

x86_64 Rust builds to work.



This change was made by manually editing the toml file, then

running:

autoninja -C out/Release tools/crates/gnrt && out/Release/gnrt gen --for-std

(after having first set enable_all_rust_features to true, to ensure gnrt

is built.)

entry.title: [Flaky Test] De-flake BottomSheetControllerTest
entry.content:
Previous Fix

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4428451



The previous fix worked locally, but there are still instances of this

happening on bots. The previous fix does correctly attach observers and

gate them.



After running the test with the flaky test checker by changing the

test names it is clear that the failure happens after the test finishes.



It looks like what happens is that the flags are reset before the

activity is finished. This means that if a Start Surface state change

happens before the activity is finished, but after the flags are reset

then the assert will be triggered.



To fix this the easiest solution is to finish the activity before the

test finishes and the flags are reset.



See: android-nougat-x86-rel for

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/android-nougat-x86-rel/222697/overview

for proof that this worked as it passed flaky test bot with modified

test names.

entry.title: [BSC]: Defer navigations and browser initiated requests when required
entry.content:
This CL implements throttling in browser requests that require a short

lived cookie that is expired.

When the request is throttled:

- `GoogleURLLoaderThrottle` will notify

`BoundSessionRequestThrottledListener` (this will always be in process

communication).

- `BoundSessionRequestThrottledListener` will cancel the request during

shutdown. The server might kill the session if there is a device bound

session and the request is missing the required cookie. If the request

is not cancelled, the user might be signed out on next startup.

- Otherwise, `BoundSessionRequestThrottledListener` notifies the

`BoundSessionCookieRefreshService` that a request is blocked. The

service will unblock the request once the cookie is fresh or the

session is terminated or timeout (not implemented yet).



The bound session params is currently null for in renderer throtling and

will be implemented in the next CL.

entry.title: CIS: Change the parsing test to test against computed value.
entry.content:
This patch changes the "reference" box to use the computed value of

width, instead of the used value.



From: https://drafts.csswg.org/cssom/#resolved-value-special-case-property-like-height



```

If the property applies to the element or pseudo-element and the resolved value

of the display property is not none or contents, then the resolved value is the

used value. Otherwise the resolved value is the computed value.

```



Since we're testing the computed value of contain-intrinsic-size, we

should compare it against a computed value of width in the reference.



R=futhark@chromium.org

entry.title: [Start] Prevent Start surface showing with the first initial tab
entry.content:
created.



The bug was caused by a timing issue: 1) both initializeState() and

createInitialTab() get a false from shouldShowOverviewPageOnStart()

when there isn't any Tab and homepage manager isn't ready. However,

after createInitialTab() creates the first Tab, #onStartWithNative()

checks shouldShowOverviewPageOnStart() again. Since there is a Tab

created, shouldShowOverviewPageOnStart() goes through a different code

path and returns true, and the Start surface is showing with an extra

tab created. In this CL, we add a flag of whether the first initial

Tab is being created, and prevent showing Start if this is true.

entry.title: [iOS] Reduce the surface exposed by BrowserInterfaceProvider
entry.content:
BrowserInterface exposes too much information. This CL tries to reduce

the amount of information exposed by introduce two new protocol to

replace BrowserInterface and BrowserInterfaceProvider.



As this protocol is mostly used to get the Browser, the protocols names

and location are reflecting that:

- BrowserProvider is used to get the Browsers

- BrowserProviderInterface is used to get the "correct" BrowserProvider



The two protocol are now located with Browser as they are mostly

ways of getting it.



There is still some information in the BrowserProvider that should

not be there, but it will be left for a future cleanup.



As the information currently exposed in the BrowserInterface are

needed by the SceneController, this CL also directly gives access

to the WrangledBrowser from the BrowserViewWrangler so the

SceneController (which is the only class needing to access it) can

have those information.
